Sieve License Status
====================

> Project state: Week 1 engineering phase (2026-04-27).
> See PRD v1.3 §11.3 (Open Source Strategy) and ADR-011 (repo private until Week 12 GA).

This repository contains TWO categories of content with DIFFERENT license terms.

---

## 1. Documentation (active in this repo)

Scope: `docs/`, `README.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.cursorrules`, `tasks/`, `SECURITY.md`,
       and any other Markdown / config files NOT inside a future Cargo crate.

License: **Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International
         (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)**
URL:     https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

You are free to:

  - Share — copy and redistribute in any medium or format
  - Adapt — remix, transform, build upon

Under the following terms:

  - Attribution — credit to "doskey / Sieve project" with link to this repo
  - NonCommercial — not for commercial purposes (commercial reuse requires
    written permission: doskey.lee@gmail.com)
  - ShareAlike — derivatives must use the same license

Rationale: Sieve is a commercial product (single-developer SaaS, [redacted]/month per
PRD §7.1). Documentation is published at Week 12 GA (ADR-011) for transparency
and trust narrative ("you can verify us, not just trust us" — PRD §1.2 #4), but
should not be repackaged as competitor material without permission.

---

## 2. Source Code (NOT YET IN THIS REPO)

Scope: All Rust source code (`*.rs`, `Cargo.toml`, `Cargo.lock`, `build.rs`,
       `crates/`, `fuzz/`) — to be added starting Week 1 (PRD §10.1).

License (planned):

  - **Core engine: MIT License** — published at Week 12 GA (PRD §11.3, §9 #10)
  - **Phase 2 advanced rule sets: Closed source** (PRD §11.3) — sold as part
    of paid subscription

Until Week 12 GA, the repository is fully private (ADR-011). The license file
in this directory will be replaced with the full MIT License text when source
code becomes public at GA.

---

## 3. Trademarks

"Sieve" is the project codename and may be replaced with a formal product name
between Week 6-8 (PRD §11.4 / §14 Open Question #1). Known existing usages:

  - sieve.ai (YC W22) — unrelated AI startup
  - SIEVE caching algorithm — academic paper / Linux kernel
  - Thunderbird Sieve — email filter language

Use of the name "Sieve" by third parties to refer to this project is permitted
under the documentation license terms above. Use as a product name for your
own derivative product requires written permission.

---

## 4. Contact

For commercial licensing, partnership, or trademark inquiries:

  - Email: doskey.lee@gmail.com
  - Subject prefix: [SIEVE-LICENSE]

For security vulnerabilities: see [SECURITY.md](./SECURITY.md).
For sample submissions: open a GitHub Issue with the "suspicious_sample" template.

---

## 5. Why Two Licenses?

Documentation and code serve different purposes, and both are published
together at Week 12 GA (see ADR-011):

  - **Docs** (CC BY-NC-SA): publish the design intent, threat model, ADRs —
    these are the "trust artifacts" that let users verify Sieve before running
    the binary. CC BY-NC-SA prevents commercial repackaging by competitors
    while permitting study, citation, and forking-for-research.

  - **Code** (MIT): at GA becomes MIT to maximize adoption (security tooling
    has network effects — wide adoption → more issue reports → faster bug fixes
    → better detection rules → better product). Phase 2 advanced rules stay
    closed because they ARE the commercial moat.

Both categories are published simultaneously at Week 12 GA — there is no
two-phase "docs first, code later" rollout. This decision is documented in
ADR-011 and not subject to change without a new ADR
(see [docs/design/ADR-INDEX.md](./docs/design/ADR-INDEX.md)).

